Pharmacology: Zolpidem is a nonbenzodiazepine hypnotic that acts primarily as a positive allosteric modulator at the GABAA receptor complex, showing a relative selectivity for receptors containing the α1 subunit. This action enhances the inhibitory effect of GABA, leading to sedation and sleep induction.
Effects: At therapeutic doses, zolpidem induces rapid sleep onset and a short duration of action. Common effects include sedation, sleep facilitation, and potential amnestic effects. In some cases, particularly when misused or in higher doses, users have reported complex sleep-related behaviors such as sleepwalking, sleep-driving, and other parasomnias.
Toxicity and Harm Potential: While effective for short-term treatment of insomnia, zolpidem carries risks including dependence, tolerance, and withdrawal symptoms with prolonged use. Its adverse effects may encompass next-day drowsiness, impaired cognitive and motor performance, and in rare cases, paradoxical reactions such as agitation. Overdose can lead to significant central nervous system depression, especially when combined with other sedatives or alcohol.
Legal Status: Zolpidem is a prescription drug and is classified as a controlled substance in many countries. In the United States, it is scheduled as a Schedule IV drug. Its availability and regulatory classification vary internationally, generally reflecting its potential for misuse alongside its therapeutic benefits.

https://www.drugbank.ca/drugs/: Zolpidem is a sedative-hypnotic medication primarily prescribed for short-term treatment of insomnia. Its brand names include Ambien, Ambien CR, Edluar, Stilnox, and Zolpimist. The drug acts selectively on omega-1 receptors, which are the alpha-1 containing GABA-A receptors, producing hypnotic effects without the muscle relaxation effects of benzodiazepines. Despite its therapeutic uses, zolpidem has abuse potential and is classified as a Schedule IV controlled substance in the United States. Street names for zolpidem include "no-gos," "zombie pills," "sleep easy," and "A-minus." Misuse can cause dependence, withdrawal symptoms, and various adverse effects including hallucinations, sleepwalking, sleep-driving, and amnesia. Users may crush extended-release formulations to bypass the controlled-release mechanism, increasing overdose risks. Recreational users sometimes co-administer zolpidem with alcohol or other CNS depressants to enhance its sedative effects, significantly increasing the risk of respiratory depression and death.
https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/: Zolpidem (brand name Ambien) is a sedative-hypnotic medication primarily used for short-term treatment of insomnia characterized by difficulties with sleep initiation. It belongs to the class of drugs known as nonbenzodiazepine receptor modulators that act on the GABA-A receptor complex. According to PubChem, it has CNS depressant effects that can lead to physical and psychological dependence, with potential for abuse and misuse. As a Schedule IV controlled substance in the US, recreational abuse occurs for its sedative, euphoric, and hallucinogenic effects, particularly when taken in higher doses than prescribed or via alternative routes of administration (crushing and snorting, injection). Street names associated with illicit use include "no-go pills," "zombie pills," "tic-tacs," "sleep easy," and "A-minus." Misuse is associated with amnesia, sleep-driving, sleep-eating, and other complex behaviors performed while not fully conscious. Withdrawal symptoms can occur with abrupt discontinuation after prolonged use, and it presents risks when combined with other CNS depressants like alcohol, opioids, or benzodiazepines.

Zolpidem is a sedative-hypnotic medication primarily prescribed for the short-term treatment of insomnia. Marketed under brand names including Ambien, Stilnox, and Sublinox, it belongs to the imidazopyridine class and works by enhancing GABA effects in the central nervous system. While medically useful, Zolpidem has become subject to misuse and abuse due to its sedative, hypnotic, and sometimes hallucinogenic effects at higher doses. Street names include "zombie pills," "no-gos," "sleep easy," and "A-minus." Recreational users may seek its amnesia-inducing and disinhibiting effects, sometimes combining it with alcohol to enhance these effects despite dangerous interactions. The drug has been implicated in cases of complex sleep behaviors including sleep-driving, sleep-eating, and making phone calls while not fully conscious. Zolpidem can cause physical dependence with withdrawal symptoms upon discontinuation and has been classified as a Schedule IV controlled substance in the United States.

Pharmacology: Zopiclone is a cyclopyrrolone derivative that acts as a positive allosteric modulator at the GABAₐ receptor complex. It binds to a site overlapping the benzodiazepine binding site, enhancing the inhibitory effects of GABA. This action produces sedative and hypnotic effects, which is why the substance is primarily used as a sleep aid in the treatment of insomnia.
Effects: At therapeutic dosages, users experience sedation, sleep induction, and anxiolytic effects. The substance contributes to improved sleep quality and decreased sleep latency, though in higher or non‐medical doses it may lead to amnesia, impaired motor coordination, or next-day grogginess and cognitive dulling. Some individuals may also experience paradoxical or dysphoric reactions.
Toxicity and Harm Potential: Although considered to have a relatively favorable profile when used as prescribed, Zopiclone carries risks of tolerance, dependence, and withdrawal symptoms following prolonged use. Overdose—especially when combined with other central nervous system depressants—can lead to respiratory depression and severe sedation. Long-term misuse has been associated with cognitive impairment and abnormal behaviors such as sleepwalking.
Legal Status: Zopiclone is a prescription-only medication in many countries and is subject to regulatory controls due to its potential for abuse and dependence. Its specific legal status varies regionally: for example, it is not approved for medical use in the United States, while in many European nations it is listed as a controlled hypnotic agent.

https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/: Zopiclone is a cyclopyrrolone-derivative hypnotic agent used for treating insomnia, classified as a Schedule IV controlled substance in the United States. It functions as a GABA-A receptor agonist, producing sedative, anxiolytic, and muscle relaxant effects. Zopiclone has a half-life of approximately 5 hours and is metabolized by the liver, with excretion occurring primarily through urine. Common side effects include bitter taste, drowsiness, dizziness, and dry mouth. The drug carries risks of dependence, withdrawal symptoms, and potential for abuse, particularly when used long-term or at higher doses than prescribed. Common brand names include Imovane and Zimovane, while street names may include "zops," "zimmers," or "Zs." Zopiclone is often used illicitly in combination with other depressants like alcohol or opioids, which significantly increases overdose risks. In recreational contexts, users may crush tablets for intranasal administration to achieve faster onset of effects, though this practice increases health risks.

Zopiclone is a non-benzodiazepine hypnotic agent used for treating insomnia. It belongs to the cyclopyrrolone class of drugs and works by enhancing the effect of GABA, an inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain. Commonly marketed under brand names like Imovane and Zimovane, Zopiclone is classified as a controlled substance in many countries due to its potential for dependence and abuse. Despite being prescribed for short-term treatment of sleep disorders, it can lead to physical and psychological dependence when used longer than recommended. Side effects include a metallic taste in the mouth, drowsiness, and dizziness. Tolerance develops quickly, leading some users to increase dosage, risking overdose. In illicit markets, it may be referred to as "zim-zims," "zoppies," or "zopiclones," and is sometimes used recreationally for its sedative effects or to counter stimulant drugs.
